ame <i>Osnabrück</i>. Switzerland has both forms. See also   Brueck  .","Jewish (from Poland and Belarus): from Polish, Belorussian, or Yiddish <i>bruk</i> ‘pavement’, possibly a metonymic occupational name for a paver."]}]},{"name":"Simon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."],"variants":[{"name":"Simen","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":14,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Simon Brugge was born about 1441, in Weobley, Herefordshire, England, his father, Thomas Brugge I, was 27 and his mother, Mrs Thomas Brugge, was 23. He married Elizabeth Walwyn about 1465, in Weobley, Herefordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died after 1474, in his hometown."},"et":{"about 1441–after 1474":"umbes 1441–pärast 1474","1441–1474":"1441–1474","